{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17411381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17411381"},"attributes":{"position":4,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2508"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473532"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:10:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:10:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2508"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1260986"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T06:24:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:02:58+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":13,"questionsAnswered":0,"marksTotal":0,"marksAttainable":0,"marksAttempted":0,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T06:25:33+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"2508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2508"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.17,0.54,0.13,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2508"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85133"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2508"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2508"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69348"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"763"},{"type":"tags","id":"1179"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2325"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2415"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29064"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44080"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/85133"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA mother brings her six-month-old son to the General Practice clinic concerned about a lump that has appeared in his right groin region. She first noticed the lump two days ago and since then has noticed that it has increased in size. The infant has been crying intensely over the last 24 hours, and the lump fluctuates in size with crying and movement. The mother did not notice any diarrhoea or constipation associated with the new lump.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe mother attended all the previous antenatal check-up and screening with no abnormal results. The baby was born prematurely at 35-weeks\u2019 gestation via elective caesarean section, with no complications during birth. He has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His vaccinations are all up to date. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the infant is crying and waving his arms. He is currently afebrile, and his vital signs are all within the normal ranges. His abdomen is soft and there is a tender immovable 2cm lump immediately lateral to the right pubic tubercle overlying the superficial skin, located superolateral to the right testicle. The left testis is situated in its normal position in the scrotum, whilst the right testis can be palpated at the apex of the scrotum.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Orchidopexy","Manual reduction","Hernia repair","Reassurance and follow-up","Percutaneous drainage"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis six-month-old infant presents with a groin lump located along the inguinal canal. An inguinal hernia in a child of this age is likely to be an indirect hernia through the deep inguinal ring. Such hernias can typically contain a section of small bowel. They typically present as an ill-defined mass in the inguinal region that may increase in size with an increase in intra-abdominal pressure i.e. coughing, straining or crying. The inguinal hernia may be painful and tender to touch, suggesting incarceration or strangulation of any contents. Risk factors for the development of such hernias include prematurity and male gender.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImmediate surgery including\u003Cstrong\u003E hernia repair\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated if there is any suggestion of strangulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EManual reduction\u003C/strong\u003E is generally not recommended in the presence of tenderness or signs of incarceration, as seen in this case. While some reducible inguinal hernias in infants can be manually reduced initially to relieve symptoms and allow for elective repair, this approach is not appropriate if there is concern for strangulation. Attempting manual reduction in a potentially strangulated hernia can force ischemic or infarcted bowel back into the abdominal cavity, delaying necessary surgical intervention and increasing the risk of perforation and sepsis. Given that this infant\u0027s lump is tender, immovable, and has been progressively increasing in size, incarceration is strongly suspected, and immediate surgical repair is the safest approach. Furthermore, inguinal hernias in infants do not resolve spontaneously and have a high risk of incarceration and strangulation, making elective repair necessary even in reducible cases. Therefore, while manual reduction may be considered in early, non-tender incarceration, the presence of tenderness in this case warrants urgent surgical intervention without attempting bedside reduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrchidopexy\u003C/strong\u003E is a surgical procedure to reposition and secure an undescended testis within the scrotum, typically performed between 6\u201312 months of age to reduce the risk of infertility and malignancy. It is not appropriate in this case, as the right testis is already palpable in the scrotum, and the lump is separate from the testicle, making an inguinal hernia the more likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance and follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E is not the appropriate management as inguinal hernias in infants often do not resolve, and the risk of incarceration and strangulation is high in such patients. Therefore, immediate surgery is necessary to prevent such complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous drainage\u003C/strong\u003E might be appropriate if it was thought that this swelling was an abscess - but there is little to suggest such a diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Urgent surgery is required in infants with inguinal hernia, particularly if there is any suggestion of strangulation.","Manual reduction should not be attempted in a tender, immobile inguinal lump, as it may mask ischemic bowel and delay necessary surgical intervention."],"references":["Wang KS. American Academy of Pediatrics: Assessment and management of inguinal hernia in infants. Pediatrics 2012;130:768-73. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23008462/","Chong AJ, Fevrier HB, Herrinton LJ. Long-term follow-up of pediatric open and laparoscopic inguinal hernia repair. J Pediatr Surg 2019;54:2138. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30885559/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69348"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2508"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69348"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-14T20:15:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-14T20:16:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2508"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85133"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"de